body:
Good evening,

The [TcpStream struct](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/net/struct.TcpStream.html) requires to use the same object for reading and writing. This is a problem as you can't do that:

```rust
use std::net::TcpListener;
use std::io::prelude::*;
use std::io::BufReader;

fn main() {
    let listener = TcpListener::bind("127.0.0.1:8080").unwrap();
    let mut stream = listener.accept().unwrap().0;
    let mut bufferedStream = BufReader::new(&stream);
    let mut line = String::new();

    loop {
        bufferedStream.read_line(&mut line).unwrap();
        print!("Message received: {}", line);
        stream.write_all(b"Hello from server\n").unwrap();
    }
}
```

gives you the error:
```
error[E0502]: cannot borrow `stream` as mutable because it is also borrowed as immutable
  --> bench/sockets/1.rs:14:9
   |
8  |     let mut bufferedStream = BufReader::new(&stream);
   |                                             ------- immutable borrow occurs here
...
12 |         bufferedStream.read_line(&mut line).unwrap();
   |         -------------- immutable borrow later used here
13 |         print!("Message received: {}", line);
14 |         stream.write_all(b"Hello from server\n").unwrap();
   |         ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ mutable borrow occurs here
```

I am missing something or is it a bad design of the language/library?

Thank you for your time,
